==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Saxon [[barn]], Old High German [[barn]], Old Norse [[barn]], Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐍂𐌽]].  Related to [[beran]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bæarn/

===Noun===
'''bearn''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''bearn''')
# a [[child]], especially a [[son]]
#:''Bearn Godes'': Son of God.  (''Codex Vercellensis'')


